body:
Like a well-watered garden,
I couldn’t help the urge to be around you;
Like a wonderful childhood Christmas,
You are the best that I’ve ever had. 

Like winning in a game of chance,
I couldn’t understand how you fell for me;
Like the soft rain on a parched surface,
You raised my hopes;

Like a fairy-tale princess,
Everybody hoped for the best for you;
Like a classic folktale,
Your taste was just enchanting;

Just like home,
There will never be anyone like you;
Like an old saying,
Your cut shall be the deepest;

Like the sun,
I felt your warmth from a distance;
Like breast milk, 
You nourished us, who delighted in you;

Like a fossil,
Your memories shall forever be stocked
In the chambers of my soul;

Like a wonderful dream,
I wish to have you again, and for real
MAY YOU REST IN PEACE NANA...

I wrote your name on the sand,
But the wind swept it away;
I engraved it on the bark,
Of a forest tree,
But wild fires consumed it;

When I carved it,
On balancing rocks,
The rain weathered it away;
When I impressed it on an iron pillar,
Rust wore it away;

At one time 
I wrote it on the sea,
But the waves tossed it away;
I can never forget you, 
But how where they to remember you?

The best I did to preserve it;
Was to engrave it 
On my heart’s tablet;
Hopefully, and maybe only there
Was it meant, eternally to be...
